{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01KomRRVGxqnnHcM5Zfuzj37","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The `createLeague` fails because the test data from a previous run was persisted. Actually wait - this is the RosterClient! The RosterClient was running previously via its Java client. But on a fresh container, the DB starts empty (create-drop). Let me check if there were prior test runs that left data:\n\nThe issue is clear now. Looking at my earlier run - I had already done a test where I sent `POST /roster/league` with `LTEST`. But wait - looking at the logs, the problem is `L1` already exists. On this fresh container, the RosterClient wasn't run. The issue is that the smoke test was run from within the container (where L1 already existed from a prior smoke test execution on the same running container).\n\nBut wait, I just started a fresh container! The error log shows the LTEST insert from my curl test at `02:13:00`, which means there was already data from a previous operation within this same container. The `LTEST` league was created by my manual curl, and then the `L1` already existed because... hmm, looking at the logs, the first smoke run inside the first container DID complete partially (it created L1 etc.) before the container was killed (exit 137).\n\nThis is a fresh container though. Let me check the most recent logs more carefully. The insert error at 02:13:00 is for the LTEST league I created manually. Let me check for L1:\n\nThe key insight: the `drop-and-create` ddl-auto means the schema is dropped and recreated each time the app starts. So on a fresh container, the DB is empty. The PREVIOUS log entries (at 02:12:42) were from a different test run. Let me check if the issue is that I tested the LTEST league first, and then the create of L1 from the smoke test tries to insert L1 (which doesn't exist yet).\n\nActually, looking more carefully at the timestamps: the 02:12:42 logs look like they're from the RosterClient being run. But the CMD in Dockerfile just runs the jar. Unless... the RosterClient might be somehow running.\n\nActually no - those Hibernate logs at 02:12:42 show many SQL operations, which seems like the smoke test running (from a previous exec). Let me just re-run cleanly:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3083,"cache_read_input_tokens":113954,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3083,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":643},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b980a48c-449a-4184-94ce-e355b0c87aac","uuid":"e5bdf269-3427-41f9-aebb-9d581fa53cfb"}
